Variables are containers for storing data values.
In C++ there are different types of variables.

int - integers(whole numbers) ex) 123,-123
size : 2 or 4 bytes


float : floating point numbers with decimals (7 decimal digits) ex.
size : 4 bytes


double - floating point numbers with decimals(15 decimal digits) ex)12e4
size : 8 byte


char - single characters surrounded by single quote ex) 'b' or 'B'
size : 1 bytes


string - text surrounded by double quotes. ex)"Hello World"
size : unknown


bool - boolean ex) true or false
size : 1 byte.



Declaring(creating) Variables
Syntax : type variableName = value;

---
//Declaring without assigning value is possible.

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main () {
	int age = 29;
	cout << age;
	return 0;
}

---
//Display Variables
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main () {
  int age = 29;
  cout << "My age is " <<age<< ". Am I late for this?";
  return 0;
}
---
//We should use descriptive identifiers for variables.
//Since programmers work together

/*
Good example.
int userAge;

Bad example
int a; //we have no idea what an 'a' means.
*/
